Locked architectural decisions

This is one of the most important schemas in Parmana.

1. Parmana does not define business signals

The signals object is policy-specific.

Examples:

Payment Policy

{
  "amount": 5000,
  "currency": "USD"
}

Loan Policy

{
  "creditScore": 780,
  "annualIncome": 120000
}

Insurance Policy

{
  "claimAmount": 25000,
  "policyAge": 5
}

Parmana has no knowledge of these fields.

2. Policy defines the schema

The request supplies:

policy.name
policy.version
policy.schemaVersion

Parmana resolves the policy and then validates the signals object against the schema associated with that policy version.

The generic signals.schema.json therefore validates only that:

the value is an object
it is not empty

Business validation occurs after policy resolution.

3. Signals are immutable

Once a Business Transaction is accepted:

Signals cannot change.
Replay always uses the original Signals.
Verification always validates the original Signals.
The Execution Trust Record stores the original Signals exactly as submitted.
4. Why additionalProperties: true

This is intentional.

If it were false, Parmana would need to know every possible business field across every domain.

Instead:

Payment systems define payment signals.
Banking systems define banking signals.
Insurance systems define insurance signals.
Healthcare systems define healthcare signals.

Parmana simply evaluates them using the resolved policy.

Canonical Principle (Locked)

Parmana is policy-driven, not domain-driven.

It never defines business fields. The resolved Policy and its associated Signal Schema define the structure and validation rules for the signals object.


{
  "$schema": "https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/schema",
  "$id": "https://schemas.parmana.ai/common/signals.schema.json",
  "title": "Signals",
  "description": "Business input evaluated by a resolved Policy.",
  "type": "object",
  "minProperties": 1,
  "additionalProperties": true,
  "examples": [
    {
      "amount": 5000,
      "currency": "USD",
      "customerType": "PREMIUM"
    },
    {
      "creditScore": 780,
      "annualIncome": 120000,
      "existingDebt": 15000
    },
    {
      "claimAmount": 25000,
      "policyAge": 5,
      "incidentType": "ACCIDENT"
    }
  ]
}